                                <dt id="endnote_en_71"><a class="pdec_endnote" href="#endnote_en_71_ref">71t</a></dt><dd> The
                                    various translations of “aimable” reveal the wealth of Nemours’s charms: “fascinating”
                                    (Perry-Lyons and Mitford), “attractive” (Ashton and Cave), “charming” (Buss). </dd>
                                <dt id="endnote_en_72"><a class="pdec_endnote" href="#endnote_en_72_ref">72t</a></dt><dd>
                                    Cave: “What indeed are they doing to me!”; Perry-Lyons: “And see what they do!”; Buss:
                                    “Alas, what else do they do!”</dd>
                                <dt id="endnote_en_73"><a class="pdec_endnote" href="#endnote_en_73_ref">73t</a></dt><dd>
                                    “Honnêteté” for a man encompasses sincerity, kindness, civility, and fairness (whereas for a
